# ~/.config/cmux/usage-sentinels.env
#
# The poller no longer stores workspace ids: cmux 0.64.15 removed stable
# workspace UUIDs, so each sentinel is resolved fresh every run by its TITLE
# LABEL (the workspace whose title starts with "5h "/"7d "). This file only
# carries OPTIONAL label overrides + the provider switch — the defaults below
# work out of the box, so an empty file (or no file at all) is fine.
#
# Setup is just: create two idle workspaces and rename them so their titles
# start with the labels, e.g.
#   cmux workspace list                                    # find the refs
#   cmux rename-workspace --workspace workspace:<N> "5h"   # then the same for 7d
# The poller then keeps the rest of each title (bar, %, reset) updated.
#
# SENTINEL_5H_LABEL=5h
# SENTINEL_7D_LABEL=7d
#
# Codex sentinel labels (only used if you enable the codex provider below). Codex
# usage is read from local ~/.codex rollout files — no token needed.
# SENTINEL_CX5H_LABEL=cx5h
# SENTINEL_CX7D_LABEL=cx7d
#
# ── Which providers show ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# The sidebar hides any provider whose sentinels don't exist, and each poller
# self-gates: if its provider isn't installed (e.g. no Claude credentials) it
# exits cleanly — no panel, no errors. So an out-of-the-box install is Claude-only
# and a missing provider can never crash anything.
#
# USAGE_PROVIDERS is the explicit override: a space-separated list of providers
# whose pollers should run (default "claude"). Drop a name to turn that poller
# into a no-op WITHOUT unloading launchd; then `cmux workspace close` its
# sentinels to remove the panel. Examples:
#   USAGE_PROVIDERS="claude"          # default — Claude meters only
#   USAGE_PROVIDERS="claude codex"    # both (once a Codex poller exists)
#   USAGE_PROVIDERS="codex"           # disable Claude here
#
# USAGE_PROVIDERS="claude"
#
# ── Workspace-group names in the sidebar (opt-in) ─────────────────────────────
# A cmux workspace GROUP's logical name and its anchor workspace's TITLE are two
# separate fields; the custom sidebar can only read the title, so a group shows
# up as the anchor's generic "Group 2" instead of its real name. With this on,
# cmux-group-sync.sh keeps each group's anchor title in sync with the group name
# (preserving any ⚡/⏳ agent marker; it only writes when the name changed). It's a
# no-op when off or when you have no groups. Enable it, then bootstrap
# com.cmux-group-sync.plist (see install.sh NEXT STEPS).
#
# GROUP_NAME_SYNC=1
